DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);


##############################################
TEXT(beginproblem());



$fname = RandomVariableName(type=>function);  #get a name for the function


Context("Numeric");
$a = random(2,10,1);
$f = Formula("sqrt($a-x)")->reduce;   #generate a radical function


Context("Interval");
$domain = Compute("(-inf,$a]");

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML


Find the domain of the function.

[`[$fname](x)=[$f]`]

[@KeyboardInstructions('Answer using interval notation. If you need to enter [`\infty`], you can type  [|inf|]* or  [|infinity|]*.  If you need to union two (or more) intervals, use the letter [|U|]*.  For example, to enter [`(\infty,5)\cup(5,10]`] you can type [|(-inf,5) U (5,10]|]*.')@]**

    [_____________]{$domain}

END_PGML


##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

To ensure that we are not taking the square root of a negative number, we need to solve the following inequality:


   [`\begin{aligned}[t]
[$a]-x & \geq 0\\
[$a]-x+x  & \geq 0+x\\
[$a] & \geq x
\end{aligned}`]

This tells us that [`x`] must be less than or equal to [`[$a]`] or be in the interval [`[$domain]`].    



END_PGML_SOLUTION


